Tutorial 11 - Introduction to Statistical Inference¶

Lecture and Tutorial Learning Goals:¶

After completing this week's lecture and tutorial work, you will be able to:

  • Describe real world examples of questions that can be answered with the statistical inference methods.
  • Name common population parameters (e.g., mean, proportion, median, variance, standard deviation) that are often estimated using sample data, and use computation to estimate these.
  • Define the following statistical sampling terms (population, sample, population parameter, point estimate, sampling distribution).
  • Explain the difference between a population parameter and sample point estimate.
  • Use computation to draw random samples from a finite population.
  • Use computation to create a sampling distribution from a finite population.
  • Describe how sample size influences the sampling distribution.

This worksheet covers parts of the Inference chapter of the online textbook. You should read this chapter before attempting the worksheet.

Virtual sampling simulation¶

In this tutorial you will study samples and sample means generated from different distributions. In real life, we rarely, if ever, have measurements for our entire population. Here, however, we will make simulated datasets so we can understand the behaviour of sample means.

Suppose we had the data science final grades for a large population of students.

Question 1.6.2
{points: 3}

Suppose we do not know the parameter value for the population of data science students (as is usually the case in real life). Compare your point estimates for the population mean from Q1.2.1 and 1.2.3 above. Which of the two point estimates is more likely to be closer to the actual value of the average final grade of the population of data science students? Briefly explain. (Hint: look at the sampling distributions for your samples of size 5 and size 100 to help you answer this question).

Student's answer Score: 0.0 / 3.0 (Top)

When you have a sample of size of 5, the mean average of the students was 69.76%. In comparison, adjusting the size to 100 lead to an average of 71.57%. This is a 1.81% difference in average.

I personally believe that the sample with a size of 5 would likely be significantly closer to the actual average final grade of a data science student. When you have a sample size of 5, you have more precision in terms of count for grades. A significant portion of the data / information present in size = 5 graph disappeared in the sample size 10 graph. In that graph, one would not be able to see the binomial split of the graph (2 bumps); but rather just a single bump, which has more resemblence to a bell curve. Overall, having a size of 5 allowed a lot of data and information to be preserved, which would likely lead to a more accurate estimation of the final average grade.

Question 2.1
{points: 3}

Describe in words the distribution above, comment on the shape, center and how spread out the distribution is. Compare this sampling distribution with samples of size 30 to the sampling distribution with samples of size 5.

Student's answer Score: 3.0 / 3.0 (Top)

For the graph above, the center appears at roughly 3 cups of coffee. We can see that over 500 students drank 3 cups of coffee per week. The distribution is pretty close-knitted. The data is pretty consistent, and has a shape similar to a bell curve.

When looking at sample size 5, we see a bell curve as well.We also notice that most students tend to drink roughly 3 cups of coffee. I would personally say the distribution is less concentrated when compared to the graph with samples of size 30. I noticed that most students drank less than 3 cups of coffee. Past 3 cups, the count of students drastically drop for each consecutive cup. Another thing of note is that the size 5 graph showed that there were more people who drank 2 to 2.5 cups of coffee than people who drank 3.5 to 4. But the sample size 30 graph shows otherwise.
